# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: box-lacrosse
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:box-lacrosse/16-inch-softball] The first set of rules was published in 1937 by the Amateur Softball Association, in the same manual as the rules for fastpitch softball.
[src:box-lacrosse/16-inch-softball] Game play for 16-inch softball is mostly consistent with standard softball game play.
[src:box-lacrosse/16-inch-softball] In contrast to standard, or 12-inch (30.48 cm) softball, it is played with a ball 16 inches (40.64 cm) in circumference.
[src:box-lacrosse/16-inch-softball] It is common to see higher arched pitching, and balls/strikes are determined by where the ball lands and crosses the batter's body.
[src:box-lacrosse/16-inch-softball] Leagues may form co-ed, all-male, or all-female teams.
[src:box-lacrosse/16-inch-softball] Additionally, teams may choose competitive or recreational leagues.
[src:box-lacrosse/16-inch-softball] There may be rule variations associated with the specific field or league of play.
[src:box-lacrosse/16-inch-softball] When playing in a co-ed league, there may be other rules that relate to the male-to-female ratio of team members and batting order.
[src:box-lacrosse/16-inch-softball] The National Softball Association (NSA) also has a published set of rules governing 16-inch softball play.
[src:box-lacrosse/16-inch-softball] The earliest known softball game of any kind was played at the Farragut Boat Club in Chicago on Thanksgiving Day 1887.
[src:box-lacrosse/16-inch-softball] The first softball was a wrapped up boxing glove and the bat was a broom.
[src:box-lacrosse/16-inch-softball] Play was encouraged by a reporter, George Hancock, who had been looking on.
[src:box-lacrosse/16-inch-softball] Harvard and Yale students played the game while waiting to hear the results of the annual Harvard-Yale football game.
[src:box-lacrosse/16-inch-softball] Until the turn of the 20th century, ball sizes ranged from 12 to 17 inches in circumference.
[src:box-lacrosse/16-inch-softball] The 16-inch softball was eventually adopted in Chicago, perhaps because it did not travel as far as the popular 12- or 14-inch balls.
[src:box-lacrosse/16-inch-softball] This also may have allowed for play on smaller playgrounds or even indoors, accommodating the Chicago landscape and climate.
[src:box-lacrosse/16-inch-softball] Another possible advantage of the 16-inch ball was that it allowed everyone to play barehanded, and gloves were a rare luxury as the Great Depression hit Chicago particularly hard.
[src:box-lacrosse/16-inch-softball] After the first national championship held in 1933 at the Century of Progress World's Fair, the sport grew in popularity.
[src:box-lacrosse/16-inch-softball] A professional league was formed that lasted through the 1950s.
[src:box-lacrosse/16-inch-softball] Teams drew crowds of over 10,000 each night.
[src:box-lacrosse/16-inch-softball] Leagues continue today but not at the same level of popularity.
[src:box-lacrosse/16-inch-softball] There are co-ed recreational leagues, competitive leagues and even a league for Chicago Public School students.
[src:box-lacrosse/16-inch-softball] Many local organizations host regular season play, typically weekly games, as well as their own playoff systems.
[src:box-lacrosse/16-inch-softball] National organizations, such as the NSA, host a variety of tournaments.
[src:box-lacrosse/16-inch-softball] By placing well in NSA tournaments, teams can qualify and compete for the 16-inch softball world series.
[src:box-lacrosse/16-inch-softball] Because local leagues may have slight variations in rules, the NSA world series is played by its own set of world series rules.
[src:box-lacrosse/16-inch-softball] One notable change is that Chicago area players, who typically are not allowed to wear gloves, may choose to wear gloves in world series games.
[src:box-lacrosse/16-inch-softball] Games are played with a deBeer Clincher 16" ball and gloves are used.
[src:box-lacrosse/16-inch-softball] In 1996 Al Maag and Tony Reibel established the 16" Softball Hall of Fame.
[src:box-lacrosse/16-inch-softball] Since inception, the organization has held annual inductee dinners attended by over 600 guests.
[src:box-lacrosse/16-inch-softball] There is a museum in Forest Park, Illinois, a suburb of Chicago.
[src:box-lacrosse/16-inch-softball] 16inchsoftballhof.com The Chicago 16" Softball Hall of Fame is a registered 501(c) not-for-profit organization.
[src:box-lacrosse/16-inch-softball] The game can be seen being played in multiple scenes in the 1986 film *About Last Night*, whose storyline was set in Chicago.
[src:box-lacrosse/2003-nll-season] The 2003 National Lacrosse League season is the 17th season in the NLL that began on December 27, 2002, and concluded with the championship game on May 3, 2003.
[src:box-lacrosse/2003-nll-season] In 2003, the NLL became the first major men's sports league in North America to feature a woman playing in a regular-season game.
[src:box-lacrosse/2003-nll-season] Ginny Capicchioni, a stand-out goaltender at Sacred Heart University, was signed by the New Jersey Storm as their third-string goaltender.
[src:box-lacrosse/2003-nll-season] She dressed for three games, though only played in one.
[src:box-lacrosse/2003-nll-season] Capicchioni collected one loose ball and made six saves while allowing 7 goals in 11 minutes of play.
[src:box-lacrosse/2003-nll-season] 2003 saw the Montreal Express suspend operations, and also saw the Washington Power move to Colorado, where even they were unprepared for the warm welcome they received in Denver.
[src:box-lacrosse/2003-nll-season] The franchise had drawn small crowds in Washington as well as in Pittsburgh and Baltimore before that, but averaged more than 16,000 fans per game in 2003, second in the league only to Toronto.
[src:box-lacrosse/2003-nll-season] The NLL gives out awards weekly for the best overall player, best offensive player, best defensive player, and best rookie.
[src:box-lacrosse/2003-nll-season] Awards are also given out monthly for the best overall player and best rookie.
[src:box-lacrosse/2003-world-indoor-lacrosse-championship] The **2003 World Indoor Lacrosse Championship** was the first World Indoor Lacrosse Championship, an international box lacrosse tournament organized by the Federation of International Lacrosse every four years.
[src:box-lacrosse/2003-world-indoor-lacrosse-championship] It took place from May 15 to 24 in Hamilton, Kitchener, Mississauga, and Oshawa, Ontario, Canada.
[src:box-lacrosse/2003-world-indoor-lacrosse-championship] Canada won the gold medal with a 21–4 victory over the Iroquois Nationals.
[src:box-lacrosse/2003-world-indoor-lacrosse-championship] The United States defeated Scotland 15–9 in the bronze medal game.
[src:box-lacrosse/2003-world-indoor-lacrosse-championship] Two other nations participated, Australia and the Czech Republic.
[src:box-lacrosse/2003-world-indoor-lacrosse-championship] Six participating teams played a round-robin in the preliminary round.
[src:box-lacrosse/2003-world-indoor-lacrosse-championship] The first place through fourth place teams each advanced to the semi-finals, while the fifth and sixth place teams advanced to the 5th place playoff.
[src:box-lacrosse/2015-world-indoor-lacrosse-championship] The **2015 World Indoor Lacrosse Championship** (**WILC**) was the fourth international box lacrosse championship organized by the Federation of International Lacrosse every four years.
[src:box-lacrosse/2015-world-indoor-lacrosse-championship] The 2015 WILC was hosted by the Onondaga Nation in the United States, south of Syracuse, New York, and took place between September 18 and 27.
[src:box-lacrosse/2015-world-indoor-lacrosse-championship] Canada defeated the host Iroquois Nationals 12–8 in the gold medal game, the same finals match-up featured in the first three indoor championships.
[src:box-lacrosse/2015-world-indoor-lacrosse-championship] Since the WILC started in 2003, Team Canada is undefeated with an overall record of 23–0.
[src:box-lacrosse/2015-world-indoor-lacrosse-championship] In the bronze medal game, the United States beat first-time participant Israel 15–4.
[src:box-lacrosse/2015-world-indoor-lacrosse-championship] Canadian Shawn Evans was the tournament MVP, scoring 10 goals and 25 assists in 5 games.
[src:box-lacrosse/2015-world-indoor-lacrosse-championship] Thirteen countries participated, 5 more than in 2011, including first-time competitors Finland, Germany, Israel, Serbia, Switzerland, and Turkey.
[src:box-lacrosse/2015-world-indoor-lacrosse-championship] Most games were held on the Onondaga Nation at the Onondaga Nation Arena and the newly built $6.5 million Onondaga Nation Fieldhouse, although the Iroquois' games versus Canada and the United States were held at War Memorial Arena in Syracuse.
[src:box-lacrosse/2015-world-indoor-lacrosse-championship] Over 10,000 fans attended the gold and bronze medal games in the Carrier Dome.
[src:box-lacrosse/2015-world-indoor-lacrosse-championship] The opening ceremonies in the sold-out War Memorial Arena featured a light show about the Haudenosaunee creation story and traditional dancing.
[src:box-lacrosse/2015-world-indoor-lacrosse-championship] After the Iroquois Nationals were not allowed to use their Haudenosaunee passports to travel to England in 2010 due to new security requirements, many international players were interested in getting their passports stamped by the Onondaga Nation.
[src:box-lacrosse/2015-world-indoor-lacrosse-championship] The documentary *Spirit Game: Pride of a Nation* explains the meaning of lacrosse to the Iroquois people and covers the Iroquois Nationals in the 2015 WILC, featuring brothers Lyle and Miles Thompson.
[src:box-lacrosse/2015-world-indoor-lacrosse-championship] The teams were divided into 3 divisions, with the 5 highest-ranked teams placed in the Blue Division and the others being split into the Red and Green Divisions.
[src:box-lacrosse/2015-world-indoor-lacrosse-championship] In the Blue Division, the top two teams advanced to the semifinals, the third and fourth teams entered the quarterfinals and the fifth team was placed in the classification bracket.
[src:box-lacrosse/2015-world-indoor-lacrosse-championship] The top two teams in both the Red and Green Divisions entered the play-in games, while the bottom two teams were placed in the classification bracket.
[src:box-lacrosse/2015-world-indoor-lacrosse-championship] Canada once again was undefeated in pool play, although the game versus the Iroquois was hard-fought.
[src:box-lacrosse/2015-world-indoor-lacrosse-championship] The Nationals led 8–4 early in the third period, but Canada outscored them 7–1 the rest of the game.
[src:box-lacrosse/2015-world-indoor-lacrosse-championship] Israel was seeded #5 and Ireland #6 in the quarterfinals.
[src:box-lacrosse/2015-world-indoor-lacrosse-championship] Finland and Australia were placed in the classification bracket.
[src:box-lacrosse/2015-world-indoor-lacrosse-championship] The gold medal game was close throughout the first half, with only two brief two-goal leads for Canada.
[src:box-lacrosse/2015-world-indoor-lacrosse-championship] Canada led 6–5 at the half, then the teams traded two-goal runs to get back to 8–7 in the early fourth quarter.
[src:box-lacrosse/2015-world-indoor-lacrosse-championship] Steven Priolo and Stephan Leblanc both scored in unsettled situations within a minute of each other for Canada to take command of the game with 10 minutes left.
[src:box-lacrosse/2015-world-indoor-lacrosse-championship] Team Canada's Curtis Dickson led all scorers with four goals, including one open-net goal, and an assist.
[src:box-lacrosse/2015-world-indoor-lacrosse-championship] His teammate Mark Matthews had four assists.
[src:box-lacrosse/2015-world-indoor-lacrosse-championship] Randy Staats and Johnny Powless both had four points for the Iroquois.
[src:box-lacrosse/2024-world-lacrosse-box-championships] The **2024 World Lacrosse Box Championships** was the sixth international men’s box lacrosse championship and first international women’s box lacrosse championship organized by World Lacrosse.
[src:box-lacrosse/2024-world-lacrosse-box-championships] It was held 20-29 September 2024 in Utica, New York, United States.
[src:box-lacrosse/2024-world-lacrosse-box-championships] Twenty-eight countries for men's teams and ten countries for women's teams competed in the 2024 World Lacrosse Box Championships.
[src:box-lacrosse/2024-world-lacrosse-box-championships] All participating teams in Pool A are awarded the 1-4 Seeds based on the Pool A Standings.
[src:box-lacrosse/2024-world-lacrosse-box-championships] The four teams with the highest point differentials in the remaining 6 Pools were awarded the 5-8 Seeds.
[src:box-lacrosse/2024-world-lacrosse-box-championships] The 8 teams with the next highest point differentials were awarded the 9-16 Seeds.
[src:box-lacrosse/2024-world-lacrosse-box-championships] Teams who lose in the Quarterfinals in the playoff bracket play in the below bracket for 5th through 8th place.
[src:box-lacrosse/2024-world-lacrosse-box-championships] Teams who lose in the First Round of the playoff bracket play in the below bracket for 9th through 11th place.
[src:box-lacrosse/2024-world-lacrosse-box-championships] Teams who are rank 3–4 in Pool B to Pool G in the below bracket for 13th through 28th place.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] 3x3 has been a basketball format long played in streets and gyms across the world, albeit in a less formal way.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] Starting in the late 2000s, 3x3 game rules started to become standardized throughout the United States, most notably through the Gus Macker and Hoop It Up tournament series, which held large events across the country that included teams and players from all skill levels.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] In 1992, Adidas launched its now-discontinued streetball competition.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] Since then, the number of 3x3 events and competitions has been steadily growing around the world.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] A Romanian organization, Sport Arena Streetball, began hosting 3x3 events in Bucharest as early as 2005, helping to grow the sport locally and regionally before formal FIBA rules were introduced.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] FIBA first test 3x3 at the 2007 Asian Indoor Games in Macau, followed by further test events in April 2008 in the Dominican Republic and October 2008 in Indonesia.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] The international debut of 3x3 under FIBA rules occurred at the 2009 Asian Youth Games, where 19 teams competed in the boys' tournament and 16 teams competed in the girls' tournament, with all games held at Anglican High School in Tanah Merah, Singapore.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] 3x3 made its worldwide competitive debut at the 2010 Summer Youth Olympics in Singapore, where 20 teams competed in both boys' and girls' categories, with games held at the Youth Space.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] Since then, FIBA has regularly held world championships in both open and U18 categories.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] Bucharest, later called the "Mecca of 3x3 basketball" by Sports Illustrated, hosted the first FIBA Europe 3x3 Championships in 2014, an event that helped establish organized 3x3 competition across Europe.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] In subsequent years, the city also hosted international 3x3 tournaments, attracting teams from outside Europe.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] FIBA developed 3x3 as a standalone discipline with its own format and regular international competitions.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] 3x3 basketball made its Olympic debut at the 2020 Summer Olympics in Tokyo.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] The 3x3 basketball variation has also been used in several tournaments, such as the Nike 3ON3 Tournament and Spokane Hoopfest, the largest 3x3 basketball tournament in the world, held annually in Spokane, Washington.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] FIBA releases from time-to-time a supplement to its official basketball rules specifically for 3x3.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] The rules state that regular FIBA rules apply to all situations not specifically addressed in the FIBA 3x3 rules.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] The current set, both in an abbreviated version and longer format, was published in August 2019.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] The current rules depart from regular full-court basketball in the following ways.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] Each team consists of three players and one substitute.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] Each team must have three players on the court when the game begins.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] The game is played on a half-court with one basket.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] The American NBA & WNBA standard half-court distance is 15.24 m (50 ft) wide & 14.33 m (47 ft) long.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] The ball is the size of a size 6 basketball (720 mm, 28.5 in) as used in the women's full-court game and its mass is that of the size 7 standard (620 g, 22 oz) used in the men's full-court game.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] A coin toss is held immediately before the game, and the winning team of the coin flip can choose to take possession of the ball at the start of the game, or take the first possession of a potential overtime period.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] In turn, this means that if the game goes into overtime, the first possession goes to the team that started the game on defense.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] The game begins with the defensive team passing the ball to the offensive team to signify the start of the game.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] All offensive players must begin outside of the arc (the opposite side of the arc of the net), and the defensive team must begin inside of the arc.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] Once the offensive team receives the ball, the clock starts.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] This exchange is also used to restart the game from any dead ball situation.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] The game is a single period of a maximum 10 minutes and the winner is the first team to score 21 or the team with the higher score at the end of the 10 minutes; scoring 21 points immediately ends the game.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] Every successful shot inside the arc, including free throws, is awarded one point, while every successful shot outside of the arc ("downtown") is awarded two points.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] After a made goal or free throw (except for technical or unsportsmanlike fouls and team fouls 10 or more; see below), play restarts with a player from the non-scoring team taking the ball directly under the basket and then dribbling or passing it to a point behind the arc.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] The defense is not allowed to play for the ball inside the block/charge semi-circle under the basket.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] In any held-ball situation, the defensive team is granted possession.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] The offensive team must attempt a shot for a goal within 12 seconds.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] An offensive player may also not dribble inside the arc with their back or side to the basket for more than 3 consecutive seconds.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] For either violation the defensive team is granted possession.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] There is a Trent Tucker Rule in which with up to 0.2 seconds left in regulation or on the shot clock, a high lob, or tip-in must be made.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] A tie in regulation time leads to an untimed overtime period, after a one-minute intermission.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] Whichever team began the game as the defensive team, begins overtime as the offensive team.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] The first team to score two points wins the game.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] Note: if a game is tied at 20 at the end of regulation, a team scoring their 21st point in overtime does not end the game.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] Substitutions can occur only in a dead-ball situation; a substitute can only enter from behind the end line opposite the basket, and the substitution becomes official once the player leaving the game has "tagged up" by making physical contact with the substitute.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] Each team is allowed one 30 second time-out per game.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] Each personal or technical foul counts as one team foul, while each unsportsmanlike or disqualifying foul counts as two team fouls.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] Personal fouls during the act of shooting inside the arc are awarded one free throw, while fouls during the act of shooting behind the arc and the shot is unsuccessful are awarded two free throws.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] Team fouls 7, 8 and 9 are awarded two free throws, and all team fouls thereafter are awarded two free throws and possession of the ball.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] The "bonus" rule specifically supersedes the normal rule for fouls in the act of shooting.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] The un-timed overtime period is considered extension of regulation for purpose of team fouls.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] The first unsportsmanlike foul against a player results in two free throws.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] A second unsportsmanlike foul, or a disqualifying foul, results in two free throws and possession.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] A player who commits two unsportsmanlike fouls is disqualified.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] A team loses the game by default if all of its players are disqualified.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] All technical fouls result in one free throw, with possession going to the team that was entitled to possession at that time.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] If a foul is committed that results in the non-fouling team retaining possession, i.e. a technical or "unsportsmanlike" foul, the non-fouling team will receive the exchange outside of the arc.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] Offensive fouls, if not technical, unsportsmanlike, or disqualifying, never result in free throws, regardless of the number of team fouls.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] In the case of a double foul, no free throws are awarded to either team, regardless of team foul count or whether the double fouls were unsportsmanlike.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] FIBA sees 3x3 as a major vehicle for promotion of the game of basketball throughout the world.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] FIBA Secretary General and IOC member Patrick Baumann explained: "The 3x3 concept has all the elements and skills required for basketball, it has inspired and will continue to inspire many great players in the future.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] At the same time, it is the easiest and one of the most-effective ways to bring youngsters to basketball, keep them and promote our game.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] FIBA is pursuing a strategy to implement 3x3.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] FIBA has developed a digital community that acts as a repository for all FIBA-endorsed 3x3 events worldwide and offers all players an individual world ranking based on the points earned by players at FIBA-endorsed 3x3 events.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] Any event around the world can become FIBA-endorsed by using FIBA's freeware, EventMaker, to organise the event.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] All FIBA-endorsed 3x3 events are classified within an established competition hierarchy, thus forming an official competition network.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] The pinnacle of this competition network is the FIBA 3x3 World Tour, which includes a series of World Tour Masters and one Final.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] A team can qualify for a World Tour Masters by playing in any of the designated World Tour qualifiers.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] The North American National Basketball Association (NBA) has also embraced 3x3.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] Since 2016, the NBA has held a summer series of tournaments known as "Dew NBA 3X", where local amateur players from around the US compete in regional events for cash prizes and a finals berth.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] The men's and women's NBA 3X champions then advance to the USA Basketball national 3x3 championship to potentially represent their country internationally.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] These tournaments also include live music performances, 3-point shooting contests for fans, an *NBA 2K* eSports competition, and appearances from current NBA players.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] The qualification system for the FIBA 3x3 World Cups for men and women differs radically from the system used for FIBA full-court competitions.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] According to *The New York Times*, 3x3 has "an unusual qualifying system designed to grow the sport all year long as much as find the best teams for the World Cup." National team entries are based strictly on a country's official 3x3 ranking.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] The ranking system for national teams also considers individual player rankings.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] For example, the US women's team qualified for the 2018 World Cup while the men's team did not, even though the men were ranked higher than the women on the cutoff date.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] Participating in a FIBA-sanctioned 3x3 event can earn ranking points; according to a FIBA executive, "Andorra has heavy participation every weekend." The current concentration of ranking events in Europe makes it more difficult for non-European nations, especially the US, to qualify.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] The aforementioned FIBA executive, when asked about the prospect of the 2020 Olympic debut of 3x3 potentially lacking any participation from the US, admitted that "a lot of teams want to beat the US.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] After the 2010 Summer Youth Olympics, FIBA established a regular World Cup that always includes men and women competing simultaneously in open, U23 and U18 categories.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] World Cups are played every year, except in years when there are Youth Olympic Games or Olympic Games.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] The COVID-19 pandemic caused the cancellation of the 2020 event.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] Classification to the World Cup is based on the 3x3 Federation Ranking, which ranks all National Federations based on the 3x3 Individual World Ranking points of their top 100 nationals in the respective category (i.e. men, women, U23 men, U23 women, U18 men, and U18 women).
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] 3x3 basketball became a regular European Games contest since its introduction at the 2015 European Games in Baku, Azerbaijan.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] 3x3 basketball made a debut in Olympic programme for the 2020 Summer Olympics in Tokyo, Japan, for both men and women.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] 3x3 basketball was included in 2022 Commonwealth Games in Birmingham, England.
[src:box-lacrosse/3x3-basketball] After the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine, FIBA banned Russian teams and officials from participating in FIBA 3x3 Basketball competitions.
[src:box-lacrosse/aflx] The AFL held two official Australian Football League (AFL) pre-season AFLX competitions featuring senior AFL clubs and players, in 2018 and 2019, but these were unpopular with spectators and did not return in 2020.
[src:box-lacrosse/aflx] The variation continues to be promoted by the AFL Commission as a participation sport in development regions and areas, and particularly where full-sized cricket grounds are not available.
[src:box-lacrosse/aflx] Since the COVID-19 pandemic, AFLX has been merged with AFL 9s and retained only the X brand, co-branding AFL 9s as Junior X, Youth X and Senior X and aligning it with the more widely established 9-a-side format.
[src:box-lacrosse/aflx] The rules of the game differed from standard Australian rules football in some significant ways.
[src:box-lacrosse/aflx] The game was played on a rectangular soccer-sized pitch, allowing matches to be hosted by stadiums that usually lacked the suitable field dimensions for Australian rules football.
[src:box-lacrosse/aflx] AFLX was first trialled at Arden Street Oval in January 2017.
[src:box-lacrosse/aflx] Two months later, it was trialed at was first trialled on a soccer pitch at Lakeside Stadium in a match between the Port Melbourne Football Club and Coburg Football Club.
[src:box-lacrosse/aflx] AFLX pre-season competition was launched by AFL chief executive officer Gillon McLachlan at Docklands Stadium on 6 February 2018.
[src:box-lacrosse/aflx] McLachlan said that AFLX would help promote football internationally.
[src:box-lacrosse/aflx] The 2018 competition attracted more than 40,000 fans to tournaments in Adelaide, Melbourne and Sydney.
[src:box-lacrosse/aflx] In Melbourne, TV ratings were reported as "modest" by AFL standards, with the three events drawing an average five-city metro audience of over 120,000 on Channel Seven's secondary channels.
[src:box-lacrosse/aflx] The AFL made several rule tweaks midway through the second season in attempt to make it higher scoring by inflating the scoring points for behinds from 1 to 2, goals from 6 to 12 and Super Goals from 10 to 20.
[src:box-lacrosse/aflx] Whitten Legends Game was also played under "EJX" (modified version of AFLX named after E J Whitten) at AAMI Park in Melbourne.
[src:box-lacrosse/aflx] It attracted just 6,000 spectators, the lowest in the series history.
[src:box-lacrosse/aflx] AFLX did not return as a senior AFL competition in 2020, as AFL had a greater focus on AFLW.
[src:box-lacrosse/aflx] Post the COVID-19 pandemic, the AFL increased the number of players to 9, effectively merging AFLX with AFL 9s and aligning with the widely established 9-a-side format.
[src:box-lacrosse/aflx] The reception to the two AFL pre-season competitions among fans and the media was mostly poor, with ABC Radio Grandstand journalist Richard Hinds being particularly savage in labelling it a "hollow, unappealing, pressure-free, atmosphere-deficient, oval-in-a-rectangle hole yawn-fest".
[src:box-lacrosse/aflx] Con Stavros of RMIT's school of Economics, Finance and Marketing, expressed doubts about the potential of AFLX to export Australian rules football but acknowledged that using rectangular playing fields instead of the standard cricket ones would make such expansion easier.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] The game originated in the 1930s in Canada, where it is more popular than field lacrosse.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] While there are 62 total members of World Lacrosse, only fifteen have competed in international box lacrosse competition.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Only Canada, the Haudenosaunee Nationals and the United States have finished in the top three places at the World Indoor Lacrosse Championships.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] The most prestigious domestic competition is the National Lacrosse League.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Lacrosse is a traditional indigenous people's game and was first encountered by Europeans when French Jesuit missionaries in the St.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Lawrence Valley witnessed the game in the 1630s.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Lacrosse for centuries was seen as a key element of cultural identity and spiritual healing to the people of Turtle Island.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] It originated as a field game and was adopted first by Canadian, American, and English athletes as a field game, eventually settling on a 10 v 10 format.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Box lacrosse is a modern version of the game that was invented in Canada during the 1920s and 1930s.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Joseph Cattarinich and Leo Dandurand, owners of the National Hockey League's Montreal Canadiens in the 1920s, led the participating ice hockey arena owners to introduce the new sport.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] In the 1930s, 6 v 6 indoor lacrosse came to be played in the summer in unused hockey rinks.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Canadians adopted the new version of the sport quickly.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Eventually, it became the more popular version of the sport in Canada, supplanting field lacrosse.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] The form was also adopted as the primary version of the game played on Native American reservations in the US and Canada by Iroquois and other Native peoples.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] It is the only sport in which the American indigenous people are sanctioned to compete internationally, participating as the Iroquois Nationals.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] However, many field lacrosse enthusiasts viewed the new version of the sport with negativity.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] The first professional box lacrosse games were held in 1931.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] That summer, the arena owners formed the *International Lacrosse League*, featuring four teams: the Montreal Canadiens, Montreal Maroons, Toronto Maple Leafs, and Cornwall Colts.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] In the wake of the original *International Lacrosse League* opened the *American Box Lacrosse League* featuring six teams: two in New York City, and one each in Brooklyn, Toronto, Boston, and Baltimore.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] The league played to small crowds on outdoor fields such as Yankee Stadium and Fenway Park, before closing midway through its inaugural season.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Lacrosse was officially declared Canada's National Summer Sport with the passage of the National Sports Act (Bill C-212) on May 12, 1994.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] The first box lacrosse match conducted in Australia came about as part of a fund raising appeal for the Queen Victoria Hospital, Melbourne.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] The Victorian Lacrosse Association was approached by the appeal committee to stage a lacrosse match as part of a multi sport carnival at the Plaza (Wattle Path Palais) ballroom at St Kilda on 1 July 1931.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] After a lightning six-a-side (outdoor) tournament format was successfully carried out a few weeks prior, it was decided to play six-a-side for this exhibition game between MCC and a composite team from other clubs, with players wearing rubber shoes and using a softer ball for the match.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Newspaper articles at the time suggest that the sport may have even been created in Australia, with P.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Lally of the famous Canadian lacrosse stick manufacturing company requesting a copy of the rules of the game from the VLA Secretary.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] By 1933, box lacrosse matches were being played in Adelaide, Brisbane, and Perth.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] This new version of the game however did not overtake the traditional version of lacrosse in popularity in Australia as happened in Canada.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] The Canadian Lacrosse Association began sponsoring box lacrosse.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] In 1932, the Mann Cup, the most prestigious lacrosse trophy in Canada, was contended for under box lacrosse rules for the first time.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Previously, the national senior men's lacrosse championship, awarded since 1901, was competed for under field lacrosse rules.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] The Mann Cup is an annual tournament that presents the champion of the Western Lacrosse Association and Major Series Lacrosse in a best of seven national championship.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] A few years later, in 1937, the Minto Cup, which had been the professional trophy in the 1910s and 20s, began being awarded under box lacrosse rules to the junior men's champions.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Currently the Canadian Lacrosse Association oversees the Mann Cup, the Minto Cup, the Presidents Cup (Senior B national championship) the Founders Cup (Junior B national championship) all under box lacrosse rules.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Briefly in 1939, a professional box lacrosse league started up in California, called the *Pacific Coast Lacrosse Association*.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] This four team league also folded shortly after opening.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Professional box lacrosse did not return to the United States again until 1968 when the Portland Adanacs and Detroit Olympics franchises played in the National Lacrosse Association, a circuit that folded after one summer season.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] A new professional indoor lacrosse league was created in the 1970s with the formation of the original National Lacrosse League.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] This league opened in 1974 with teams in Montreal, Toronto, Rochester, Syracuse, Philadelphia, and Maryland.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] For the 1975 season, Rochester moved to Boston, Syracuse moved to Quebec City, and Toronto moved to Long Island.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Thus, by its second year, the original NLL was playing in all major league arenas: the Colisée de Québec, the Montreal Forum, the Boston Garden, Nassau Coliseum, the Spectrum, and the Capital Centre.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] When the two wealthier '75 NLL franchises, Philadelphia and Maryland, finished out of the playoffs, and with Montreal losing access to the fabled Montreal Forum in the upcoming season due to the 1976 Montreal Olympic Games, the league folded after two seasons due to financial uncertainty.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] The rebirth of professional box lacrosse in the United States came on March 13, 1986, with the formation of the Eagle Pro Box Lacrosse League, which was incorporated by Russ Cline and Chris Fritz.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] The league originated with four teams: the Philadelphia Wings, New Jersey Saints, Washington Wave, and Baltimore Thunder, and unlike box lacrosse generally, was played during the winter.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] The league rebranded itself as the Major Indoor Lacrosse League (MILL) immediately after its inaugural season, and in 1998 renamed itself again, this time to the NLL.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] In 1998, the NLL entered into the Canadian market for the first time with the Ontario Raiders, renamed after 1 season to the Toronto Rock.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] In 2025, the NLL consists of 14 teams, evenly split between the United States and Canada.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] The league is very volatile, with teams moving or folding every few years.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] The most recent change is the move of the Firewolves from Albany, New York, to Oshawa, Ontario.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] The oldest team that has not moved from its original location is the Buffalo Bandits, who were founded in 1992 and are the league's most successful club, having won seven championships.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] A semi-professional league called the Arena Lacrosse League was formed in 2017, with all teams in Ontario.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] It signed an agreement with the NLL to serve as its official minor league.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] On June 29, 2022, a group of lacrosse fans announced a new league called the Professional Box Lacrosse Association.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] The league spokesperson identified nine teams which will be in cities in the United States.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] It barely lasted a single season, ceasing operations just a few weeks after games began.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] During play, a team consists of six players: a goaltender and five "runners".
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] A runner is any non-goalkeeper position player, including forwards, transition players, and defenders.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Runners usually specialize in one of these roles and substitute off the field when the ball moves from one end to the other.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] When the sport originated teams played with six runners.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] However, in 1953 the sixth runner, a position called rover, was eliminated.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] The goalkeeper can be replaced by another runner, often when a delayed penalty has been called on the other team or at the end of games by teams that are behind to help score goals.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] A player's lacrosse stick must be between 40 and 46 inches (1.02–1.17 m) in length (youth levels may use shorter sticks).
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] In most leagues, the use of a traditional wooden stick is allowed.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] However, almost no players use wooden sticks any more, preferring aluminum or another metal, and a plastic head.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] In the NLL, wooden sticks are not allowed.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Besides a stick, each player must also wear a certain amount of protective equipment, including a lacrosse helmet with face mask, lacrosse gloves, arm and shoulder pads, and back/kidney pads.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] In some box leagues, especially the NLL, the five "runners" wear helmets specifically designed for box lacrosse.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] These helmets consist of a hockey helmet with a box lacrosse face mask attached instead of a hockey cage.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] During a typical game the number of officials can range from one to three, depending on the league and level of play.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] In most games there are at least two referees: a lead official and a trail official.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] In NLL games there are three officials per game.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] The goaltender's responsibility is to prevent the opposition from scoring goals by directly defending the net.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] The 9 feet (2.7 m) to 9 feet 3 inches (2.82 m) radius area surrounding the net is called the "crease".
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Players except for the goaltender may not enter the crease while playing the ball.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Punishments for crease infractions include a change of possession, resetting of the time-clock, or a possible two-minute penalty depending on the infraction.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Opposing players may not make contact with the goaltender while he is in the crease.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Once he leaves the crease, however, he loses all goaltender privileges.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Even as box lacrosse grows in the United States, the American goalkeeper is a rarity.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] The skills required to be a successful field lacrosse goaltender and a successful box lacrosse goaltender are very different and do not lend well to one another.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] A defender is a player position whose primary responsibility is to prevent the opposing team from scoring.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Unlike in field lacrosse where some defensive players carry longer sticks, all box lacrosse defenders play with a maximum 46 inches (1.2 m) long stick.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] A transition player is a player whose responsibility is primarily to play during defensive situations with an offensive mindset.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] The goal of this player is to create fast breaks and scoring opportunities.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] An attack is a player position on the field whose responsibility is primarily offensive.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Typically, an Attack is dominant throwing with one hand or the other, and will primarily play on that side of the floor.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Some players, known as creasemen, do not focus on one side or the other.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] These players instead focus their offensive attention near the crease area in front of the goaltender.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] The playing area of box lacrosse is typically an ice hockey rink during the summer months.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] The playing surface is usually the concrete floor underneath the melted ice.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Generally the playing area is 180 feet (55 m) to 200 feet (61 m) in length and 80 feet (24 m) to 90 feet (27 m) in width.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] The NLL plays on artificial turf placed on top of the ice.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Some leagues, and teams that have dedicated box lacrosse arenas (such as the Iroquois), have outfitted their playing surface with artificial turf similar to the NLL.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Box lacrosse goal dimensions are traditionally 4 feet (1.2 m) wide by 4 feet (1.2 m) tall.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] In the NLL, the dimensions are slightly larger at 4 feet 9 inches (1.45 m) wide by 4 feet (1.2 m) tall.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] These nets are significantly smaller than field lacrosse nets which measure 6 feet (1.8 m) wide by 6 feet (1.8 m) tall.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] A traditional game played under the rules of the Canadian Lacrosse Association consists of three periods of 20 minutes each (similar to ice hockey), with the teams changing ends each period.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] The NLL plays four 15-minute quarters rather than three periods.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] If the game is tied at the end of regulation play, a 5-minute overtime (15 in NLL) can be played.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Overtime may or may not be sudden victory, depending on the league.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Each period, and after each goal scored, play is restarted with a face-off.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] If a ball travels over the boards and outside of the playing area, play is restarted by possession being awarded to the opposing team to that which last touched the ball.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] During play, teams may substitute players in and out freely.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Sometimes this is referred to as "on the fly" substitution.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Substitution must occur within the designated exchange area in front of the players bench in order to be legal.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] The sport utilizes a shot clock and the attacking team must take a shot on goal within 30 seconds of gaining possession of the ball.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] In addition, players must advance the ball from their own defensive end to the offensive half of the floor within 10 seconds (8 in NLL).
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] For most penalties, the offending player is sent to the penalty box and his team has to play without him and with one less player for a short amount of time.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Most penalties last for two minutes unless a major penalty has been assessed.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] The team that has taken the penalty is said to be playing shorthanded while the other team is on the power play.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] A two-minute minor penalty is often called for lesser infractions such as slashing, tripping, elbowing, roughing, too many players, illegal equipment, holding, or interference.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Five-minute major penalties are called for especially violent instances of most minor infractions that result in intentional injury to an opponent, as well as for fighting.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Players are released from the penalty box when either the penalty time expires, or the opposition scores a goal (or three goals for the instance of a major penalty).
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] At the officials' discretion a ten-minute misconduct penalty may be assessed.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] These are served in full by the penalized player, but his team may immediately substitute another player on the playing area unless a minor or major penalty is assessed in conjunction with the misconduct (a "two-and-ten" or "five-and-ten").
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] In that case, the team designates another player to serve the minor or major; both players go to the penalty box, but only the designee may not be replaced, and he is released upon the expiration of the two or five minutes.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] In addition, game misconducts are assessed for deliberate intent to inflict severe injury on an opponent.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] A player who receives a game misconduct is ejected and may not return to play.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Receiving two major penalties in a game risks a game misconduct.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] A penalty shot, where a player from the non-offending team is given an attempt to score a goal without opposition from any defending players except the goaltender, may be awarded under certain circumstances.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] By rule, teams must have at least three runners in play.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] If a team commits a third penalty resulting in a "three man down" situation a penalty shot is awarded in favour of having the offending player serve in the penalty box.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] A penalty shot may also be awarded, at the referee's discretion, if a defensive player causes a foul to prevent a goal (by throwing his stick, holding, tripping, or by deliberately displacing the goal, or a defensive player intentionally falls and covers a ball in his own team's crease).
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] In the NLL, a penalty shot is awarded against any team taking a too-many-men penalty in the final two minutes of the game or overtime.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Similar to fighting in ice hockey, fighting is tolerated in professional box lacrosse.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Professional players are not automatically subject to ejection, but incur a five-minute major penalty.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] In Canadian Lacrosse Association play, players are assessed a five-minute major penalty plus a game misconduct.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Fighting in youth or club level box lacrosse is typically penalized with expulsion and suspensions.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] In 1990, when the Six Nations created the new Mohawk lacrosse league, fighting was specifically targeted as unacceptable.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Violators were ejected from the game in which the altercation occurred and given a minimum three-game suspension.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Box lacrosse is the most popular version of the sport in the Czech Republic.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] It is also played to a marginal degree in Australia, primarily by players who have played field lacrosse.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Club level box lacrosse leagues in the United States have increased the number of players exposed to the sport, including the: Baltimore Indoor Lacrosse League, the Philadelphia Box Lacrosse Association, and the Metro Area Box Lacrosse League.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] The first world championship of box lacrosse, "The Nations in 1980", was staged in several arenas in British Columbia, Canada in July 1980 involving teams representing the United States, Australia, Canada East, Canada West and the Iroquois Nationals.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Canada West (Coquitlam Adanacs) defeated the Iroquois in the nationally televised world championship game from Pacific Coliseum in Vancouver.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] This was the first time in history that competitors from the Indigenous peoples of the Americas represented themselves in an athletic world championship competition, something that continues with the Iroquois, now known as the Haudenosaunee Nationals, competing in every championship since 2003.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] The second international box lacrosse tournament was held in 2003, with the inaugural World Indoor Lacrosse Championships.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] The competitors were national teams from Australia, Canada, the Czech Republic, the Iroquois Nationals, Scotland, and the United States.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] The 2015 WILC was hosted by the Onondaga Nation in the United States which marks the first time an international sporting event has been held on indigenous land.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Thirteen teams competed in the championship: Australia, Canada, Czech Republic, England, Finland, Germany, Iroquois Nationals, Ireland, Israel, Serbia, Switzerland, Turkey, and the United States.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Canada, Iroquois Nationals and the United States have won gold, silver, and bronze respectively in each of the World Indoor Lacrosse Championships held.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Canada has yet to lose an international game in box lacrosse.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Other international tournaments have been played.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Annually, the European Lacrosse Federation holds the Aleš Hřebeský Memorial tournament in Prague.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] This is the largest European box lacrosse tournament.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] In 2002 and 2004, the Heritage Cup was played between the United States and Canada featuring mostly players that were members of NLL teams.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] The North American Invitational is an annual tournament played in New York State featuring international teams.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] The 2026 Traditions Cup was the inaugural running of a new invitational tournament run by the NAI.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Club24Heat, from the Kahnawà:ke Reserve, won the men's division.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Israel won the women's division, and the Snake Island Muskies won the junior competition.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Historically, box lacrosse has been exclusively a men's sport.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Women who played the sport of lacrosse typically played the women's field lacrosse version.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] Recently, Ontario, Alberta, Nova Scotia and British Columbia have established girls' and women's box lacrosse leagues.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] The first Women's World Championships was held in 2024 alongside the Men's tournament in Utica, New York.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] The United States defeated Canada in the final.
[src:box-lacrosse/box-lacrosse] During the 2003 NLL season, goaltender Ginny Capicchioni appeared in two preseason and one regular season games to become the only woman to make an appearance in the NLL.
